<% content_for :custom_head do %>
  <%= image_meta_tag('tutorials/led_on.jpg') %>
<% end %>

<div class="row">
  <div class="col-xs-12 col-md-offset-2 col-md-8">

    <div class="page-header">
      <h1>LED Tutorial</h1>
    </div>

    <br>

    <h3>What you'll be building</h3>

    This tutorial teaches you how to turn a light-emitting diode (LED) on and off via the internet.

    <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/340582653" width="640" height="410" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen></iframe>

    <h3>Requirements</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Raspberry Pi connected to the internet</li>
      <li>Circuit materials: LED, breadboard, wires, 330 ohm resistor</li>
    </ul>

    <br>

    <h3>Step 1: Set up the circuit</h3>
    Connect the LED to GPIO pin 4, and add a 330 ohm resistor in series.
    <br><br>
    <%= tutorial_image('tutorials/led_circuit.png') %>
    <br><br>
    <%= tutorial_image('tutorials/led_off.jpg') %>

    <br><br><br>

    <h3>Step 2: Run <%= Rails.application.config_for(:limitos)['application_name'] %> on the Raspberry Pi</h3>
    LimitOS runs on top of Raspberry Pi OS (Buster), and can be run via:
    <br>
    <%= render 'shared/install_command' %>
    <br>
    Follow the on-screen instructions to register the device afterwards.
    <br><br>
    <%= tutorial_image('tutorials/limitos_run.gif') %>

    <br><br><br>

    <h3>Step 3: Set up the device on the <%= Rails.application.config_for(:limitos)['application_name'] %> website</h3>
    Add pin 4 as a digital output, and you can then click the "on" or "off" buttons on the website to turn the LED on or off.
    <br><br>
    <%= tutorial_image('tutorials/led_on.jpg') %>

    <br><br><br><br>

  </div>
</div>
